    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "There is `password` field in many packets, for example `Invite request`\r\n```\r\nSerialized form:\r\n\r\nLength      | Content\r\n----------- | ------\r\n`1`         | `0x5b`\r\n`4`         | `hash id`\r\n`32`        | `PK of sender`\r\n`24`        | `nonce`\r\n`1`         | `0xf6`(packet kind: invite request)\r\n`8`         | `message id`\r\n`4`         | `sender pk hash`\r\n`2`         | `length`(of nickname)\r\nvariable    | `nickname` of length `length`(UTF-8 string)\r\n`32`        | `password`(comes only when password is setted)\r\n```\r\nWhen we parse this packet we need to check if we used password.\r\nIf yes then sender would append password to packet, if not there would be no password.\r\nI think this scheme may cause inconsistency between peers.\r\nI suggest to insert flag to indicate the password is included or not.\r\nThis would permit us to parse packet only using packet itself, without checking other variable.",
    "closed_at": "2022-02-04T20:51:38Z",
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "All packets that include a password now have a length field preceding the password. However the length field is still only included if a password is set. There should be no inconsistencies between peers. The flag you're looking for is implicit in whether or not the length field is set, which can be determined by the size of the payload.\r\n\r\nSee the updated packet spec here: https://github.com/JFreegman/toxcore/blob/ngc_jf/docs/DHT_Group_Chats_Packet_Spec.md",
